<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Helical Gear" class="currentChild" href="Helical_Gear">Helical Gear</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A gear used to drive printing press rollers or cylinders in which the teeth are cut at an angle to the surface of the cylinder. Helical gears, found on newer presses, by design reduce <a title="Play" href="Play">play</a>, the unimpeded (and undesirable) movement between gears. The older <a title="Spur Gear" href="Spur_Gear">spur gear</a>, on which the teeth are cut parallel to the surface of the cylinder, generally requires a <a title="Backlash Gear" href="Backlash_Gear">backlash gear</a> to reduce play. Cylinders in which the <a title="Bearer" href="Bearer">bearer</a>s (metal rings attached to the ends of the cylinder) of the <a title="Plate Cylinder" href="Plate_Cylinder">plate cylinder</a> run in contact with those of the <a title="Blanket Cylinder" href="Blanket_Cylinder">blanket cylinder</a> commonly use spur gears, while those that run out of contact use helical gears to reduce play and provide a smoother drive. (See <a title="Plate Cylinder" href="Plate_Cylinder">Plate Cylinder</a>, <a title="Blanket Cylinder" href="Blanket_Cylinder">Blanket Cylinder</a> and <a title="Spur Gear" href="Spur_Gear">Spur Gear</a>.) 
</p>
